[[Dave Myers (British chef)|David Myers]] (born 8 September 1957)<ref>{{cite web|author=Graham Young |url=http://www.birminghammail.net/news/top-stories/2008/11/21/hairy-bikers-star-dave-myers-says-his-biggest-fear-is-going-blind-97319-22310419/ |title=Hairy Bikers' star Dave Myers says his biggest fear is going blind |publisher=Birmingham Mail |date=21 November 2008 |accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref> and [[Si King|Simon "Si" King]] (born 20 October 1966)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2009/10/15/hairy-biker-simon-king-in-hospital-after-crash-72703-24937562/ |title=News – Chronicle News – Hairy Biker Simon King in hospital after crash |publisher=ChronicleLive |date= |accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref> collectively known as the '''Hairy Bikers''', are British television presenters who have fronted the series ''[[The Hairy Bikers' Cookbook]]'', ''The Hairy Bikers Ride Again'', ''The Hairy Bakers'', ''[[The Hairy Bikers' Food Tour of Britain]]'', ''The Hairy Bikers' Mums Know Best'', ''Hairy Bikers' Meals on Wheels'', ''Hairy Bikers' Best of British'', ''The Hairy Bikers' Bakeation'', ''Hairy Dieters: How to Love Food and Lose Weight'', ''[[The Hairy Bikers' Asian Adventure]]'', ''The Hairy Bikers' Northern Exposure'' and ''The Hairy Bikers' Pubs That Built Britain'' for [[BBC Two]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b069hr3q|title=BBC Two - The Hairy Bikers' Northern Exposure|work=BBC}}</ref> and ''The Hairy Bikers' Mississippi Adventure'' for [[Good Food]].<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|url = http://goodfood.uktv.co.uk/shows/hairy-bikers-mississippi-adventure/|title = The Hairy Bikers make exclusive }}</ref>

==Biographies==
Both Myers and King have a background in TV and film production. Myers is a professional make-up artist, specialising in [[prosthetics]], while King served as locations manager on numerous productions including the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' films]] and ''[[Byker Grove]]''.

They met in 1992 on the set of a TV drama entitled ''The Gambling Man'' which was based on a [[Catherine Cookson]] novel. King was the second assistant director and Myers was head of prosthetics, hair and make-up on the production.<ref name=independent>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/how-we-met-simon-king--dave-myers-7976629.html 'How We Met' at The Independent.co.uk] Retrieved 8 September 2013</ref> Both have a [[tattoo]] of [[Che Guevara]] on their right arm. Simon King is a supporter of [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].

==TV shows==
[[File:Hairy Bikers - Mums Know Best Book Cover.jpg|thumb|The front cover of ''Mums Know Best – The Hairy Bikers' Family Cookbook'']]
The duo appeared on the [[BBC]]'s ''[[The Hairy Bikers' Cookbook]]''. Their TV shows are a mixture of cookery and [[travel journal|travelogue]], using a similar format and style to that previously associated with [[Keith Floyd]], including the habit of frequently referring to the cameraman and other crew. Most shows feature the pair riding [[motorbike]]s, including the [[BMW R1200GS]], [[BMW F650 single|F650GS]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldofbmw.com/content/article.asp?article=529&artDate=31/05/2006%2014:08:37|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090710023434/http://www.worldofbmw.com/content/article.asp?article=529&artDate=31%2F05%2F2006%2014%3A08%3A37|archivedate=10 July 2009|title=Two Hairy Bikers and one lucky winner|date=May 31, 2006|deadurl=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/showbiz/s/1063073_crumbs__more_hairy_moments |title=Crumbs – more hairy moments |publisher=[[Manchester Evening News]] |last=Welch |first=Andy |date=18 August 2008 |accessdate=9 January 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081123041320/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/showbiz/s/1063073_crumbs__more_hairy_moments |archivedate=23 November 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> and [[Triumph Rocket III]]. The show also features elements of the [[Two Fat Ladies]] format, including regular [[banter]] between the two stars, use of various unusual cooking locations and the use of motorbikes.

The pair have appeared on several episodes of ''[[Saturday Kitchen]]'' on the BBC, as well as on ''[[Richard & Judy]]'' on [[Channel 4]].  They both appeared on a celebrity chefs special of ''[[The Weakest Link]]'' and in the première episode of ''James Martin's Brittany'' with ''Saturday Kitchen'' presenter [[James Martin (chef)|James Martin]].<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv-entertainment/tv/todays-tv/2008/08/31/james-martin-s-brittany-115875-20719454/ | publisher= The Daily Mirror | title= James Martin's Brittany | date= 31 August 2008 | accessdate= 16 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.hairybikers.com/blog/index.php?article=64 | title= HAIRY BIKERS DOUBLE WHAMMY on Tonight's Television | publisher= The Hairy Bikers | work= The Hairy Blog | date= 1 September 2008 | accessdate= 16 January 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

In summer 2009 they filmed a 30-part daytime series for [[BBC Two]], ''[[The Hairy Bikers' Food Tour of Britain]]'', which aired weekdays starting on 24 August 2009. The series saw them visit a different county each day and cook what they considered to be that county's signature dish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hairybikers.com/blog/index.php?article=102|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802031721/http://www.hairybikers.com/blog/index.php?article=102|archivedate=2 August 2009 |title=The Hairy Bikers rev up for their Food Tour of Britain for BBC Two Daytime|date=July 15, 2009|website=hairybikers.com}}</ref>

In October 2009, filming of a BBC Christmas show featuring the Hairy Bikers was halted after King was injured in an accident on Tyneside. King came off his bike when a car pulled out in front of him, while he was riding through [[Gosforth]] during rush hour. His TV partner Dave Myers was riding some distance behind him. King was taken to [[Newcastle General Hospital]] for treatment to bruising to his right leg and ribs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/tv-film/tv-news/2009/10/16/hairy-bikers-star-simon-king-injured-after-motorcycle-accident-86908-21751143/ |title=Hairy Bikers star Simon King injured after motorcycle accident |publisher=Daily Record |date=16 October 2009 |accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref> The hour long ''Hairy Bikers' Twelve Days of Christmas'' was shown on BBC2, 16 December 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/ListingsServlet?event=10&channelId=105&programmeId=107545499&jspLocation=/jsp/prog_details_fullpage.jsp |title=UK TV listings schedule – What's on TV tonight? |publisher=Radio Times |date= |accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref>

A new six part series titled ''The Hairy Bikers: Mums Know Best'' commenced broadcast in early January 2010 on BBC2.<ref>{{cite web|author=kazy |url=http://www.hairybikers.com/shows/mums-know-best-series-1/1326 |title=Mums Know Best – Series 1 – Shows |publisher=Hairy Bikers |date=20 January 2010 |accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref>

On 25 October 2010 a new 40 episode series, ''The Hairy Bikers' Cook Off'', was launched on BBC2. The programme includes a cook off between two families and celebrity guests.

From January to May 2010, the Hairy Bikers performed their "Big Night Out" show in theatres throughout the UK. Directed by [[Bob Mortimer]], the show was a fun mixture of cooking and chat with a little song and dance thrown in. It explored their youth, how they met and their love of food.
In October 2010, the Hairy Bikers were guests on the BBC TV series ''[[Genius (UK TV series)|Genius]]'' hosted by comedian [[Dave Gorman]].

In June 2011, the Bikers appeared in the second series of ''Mum Knows Best''. The series, made up of eight episodes, featured three 'Star Mums' whose recipes were tested and shared with the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hairybikers.com/shows/mums-know-best-series-2/1325 |title=Mums Know Best – Series 2 – Shows |publisher=Hairy Bikers |date= |accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref> In addition, one of the episodes featured the world-famous 'pie village' of [[Denby Dale]], where the [[Denby Dale Pie Company]] are based.

October 2011 saw a new series, ''Meals on Wheels'', air on BBC2. The series fronted a campaign to save local 'meals on wheels' services around the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hairybikers.com/shows/meals-on-wheels/1324 |title=Meals on Wheels – Shows |publisher=Hairy Bikers |date= |accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref>

From November to December 2011, the Bikers appeared in a 30-part BBC series called ''Hairy Bikers: Best of British'', airing at 3:45pm on BBC2 (apart from the show's final week, in which it aired on BBC1). The series celebrated British recipes and championed local produce. In January 2012, continuing into February, BBC2 showed hour long re-versions including recipes from various episodes of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hairybikers.com/shows/best-of-british/1458 |title=Best of British – Shows |publisher=Hairy Bikers |date= |accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref>

After they had signed new contracts with the BBC in 2011, a new series was commissioned. ''The Hairy Bikers' Bakeation'' saw them on a gastronomic road trip, looking at baking across [[Europe]], from [[Norway]], the [[Low Countries]] ([[Netherlands]], [[Belgium]] and [[Luxembourg]]), [[Germany]], [[Eastern Europe]] ([[Slovakia]], [[Hungary]] and [[Romania]]), [[Austria]], [[Italy]] and [[France]] to [[Spain]].

In March 2012, [[Good Food]] commissioned ''The Hairy Bikers' Mississippi Adventure'', the duo's first series for the channel. [[UKTV]] gave a description of the series: "In this ultimate food and music pilgrimage, the perennially popular Hairy Bikers are getting back in the saddle as they explore the length of the iconic [[Mississippi River]] in America in pursuit of the delicious roots of soul food and Southern music." The series will be produced by [[Mentorn|Mentorn Media]] and the Bikers' first interactive [[iOS]] app, also produced by Mentorn, will be released to accompany the series.<ref name="autogenerated1"/>

In August 2012, ''Hairy Dieters: How to Love Food and Lose Weight'' showed how the Hairy Bikers' radically changed lifestyles, but stayed true to their love of great food, as they embarked on a campaign to lose two-and-a-half stones ({{convert|15.8|kg|lb|abbr=on}}) in three months, and comfortably passed their target weights.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00vq8c6 |title=BBC Two – Hairy Dieters: How to Love Food and Lose Weight |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref>

In August 2012, Myers appeared on Channel 4's ''[[Countdown (game show)|Countdown]]'' in dictionary corner, and again in January 2013.

Myers took part in the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 11)|eleventh series]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'', partnering [[Karen Hauer]]. On 10 November 2013 he was the sixth celebrity to be eliminated from the contest.<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/strictly-come-dancing-result-dave-2717213 "Strictly Come Dancing's Dave Myers exits the show but says "I've had the time of my life", ''Mirror TV'', 10 November 2013]. Accessed 11 November 2013</ref>

In September 2016 the pair premiered ''[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b07v6kyb The Hairy Bikers - Chicken & Egg]'' on BBC 2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b07v6kyb|title=Hairy Bikers - Chicken & Egg - BBC Two|website=BBC|access-date=2016-09-28}}</ref>  The show featured the pair biking across Europe, America, and the Middle East in search of the best chicken and egg recipes.  The six episodes feature the UK, France, Morocco, USA and Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hairybikers.com/shows/view/the-hairy-bikers-chicken-egg#DQ1Iv3QsztkWVP4W.97|title=The Hairy Bikers - Chicken & Egg - TV Shows - Hairy Bikers|last=Bikers|first=Hairy|website=Hairy Bikers|access-date=2016-09-28}}</ref>

In 2018 Hairy Bikers appeared in [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09lb54n Hairy Bikers' Mediterranean Adventure] on BBC2 <ref>{{cite web|title=BBC Two - Hairy Bikers&#039; Mediterranean Adventure|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09lb54n|accessdate=12 May 2018|quote=The Hairy Bikers seek out the authentic flavours of the Mediterranean.}}</ref>

==American version==
[[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]] released an [[Hairy Bikers (U.S. TV series)|American version of the show]] starring Paul Patranella and Bill Allen. The show aired for 10 episodes and was spoofed in an episode of ''[[South Park]]'' entitled "[[A History Channel Thanksgiving]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.com/shows/hairy-bikers/episodes/ |title=Hairy Bikers – Episode Guide – |publisher=History.com |date= |accessdate=28 November 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109041219/http://www.history.com/shows/hairy-bikers/episodes |archivedate=9 November 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southparkstudios.com/full-episodes/s15e13-a-history-channel-thanksgiving |title=A History Channel Thanksgiving (Season 15, Episode 13) – Full Episode Player |publisher=South Park Studios |date= |accessdate=28 November 2012}}</ref>

