{{For|a general, non-specific list of terms|Musical terminology}} {{Unreferenced|date=October 2017}} Many [[music]]al terms are in [[Italian language|Italian]], and many of the most important early [[composer]]s from the [[renaissance music|Italian Renaissance]] to the [[Baroque]] period were [[Italy|Italian]], and that period is when numerous musical indications were used extensively for the first time{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}. (See also [[sheet music]].)
Here are some of these expressions:
== Musical forms == {| border="1" rules="rows" align="center" width="98%" ! bgcolor="#ddffdd" | Italian term ! bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | Literal translation ! bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Definition |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[A cappella]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''in chapel style'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Sung with no (instrumental) accompaniment, has lots of harmonizing |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Aria]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" |''air'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Piece of music, usually for a singer
