== Voices == {| border="1" rules="rows" align="center" width="98%" | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Soprano]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''upper'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | The highest vocal line |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Mezzo-soprano]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''middle-upper'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Between soprano and alto |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Alto (voice)|Alto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''high'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Second-highest vocal line |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Contralto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''against high'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Alto, esp. a female alto |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Bass (voice type)|Basso]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''low'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Or "bass;" the lowest vocal line |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Basso profondo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''deep and low'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A very deep bass voice |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Coloratura soprano]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''colouring soprano'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A soprano specialised in complex, ornamented melody |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Soprano sfogato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''unlimited soprano'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A soprano who has extended her upper range beyond the usual range of a soprano |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Spinto soprano]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''pushed soprano'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A soprano whose voice, while normally of lyric weight and fluidity, can be pushed to a more forceful weight |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Squillo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''ringing'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | The resonant clarity of an operatic singer’s voice |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Tenore contraltino]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | '''' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A tenor voice capable of a slightly higher range of sustainable notes than usual |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Tenore di grazia]]''' or ‘’’Leggiero tenor’’’ | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | '''' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A lightweight, flexible tenor voice |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Tessitura]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''texture'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A singer’s comfortable range |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Falsetto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''little false'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A vocal register immediately above the modal voice range |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Falsettone]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | '''' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Falsetto, sung using the usual techniques of modal voice register |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Castrato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''castrated'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A male singer, castrated so as to be able to sing soprano (now sung by women, conventional [[countertenor]]s, or [[sopranista|sopranisti]]) |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Musico]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''musician'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Originally, a trained musician; later, a castrato or female singer |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Spinto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''pushed'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A forceful voice, between the lyric and dramatic in weight |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Passaggio]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''crossing'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A vocal range |- |}
== Tempo == {| border="1" rules="rows" align="center" width="98%" | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Tempo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''time'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | The speed of music e.g. 120 BPM |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Grave (music)|Grave]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''solemn'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Slow and solemn, slower than largo |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Largo (music)|Largo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''broad'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Slow and dignified |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Larghetto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''a little bit broad'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Not as slow as largo |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[tempo|Lentando]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''slowing'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Becoming slower |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[tempo|Lento]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''slow'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Slow |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[tempo|Tardo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''slow'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Slow |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Adagio (music)|Adagio]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ad agio, ''at ease'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Slow, but not as slow as largo |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Adagietto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''little adagio'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Faster than adagio; or a short adagio composition |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Andante (tempo)|Andante]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''at a walking pace'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Moderately slow, flowing along |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Andantino (music)|Andantino]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''slightly faster than andante'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd"| '' slightly faster than andante'' |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[tempo|Moderato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''moderately'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | At a moderate speed |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Allegretto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''a little bit joyful'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Slightly slower than allegro |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Largamente]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''broadly'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Slow and dignified |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Tempo#Terms for change in tempo|Mosso]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''moved'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Agitated |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Allegro (music)|Allegro]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''joyful; lively and fast'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Moderately fast |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Sostenuto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''sustained'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A slowing of tempo, often accompanied by legato playing |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Fermata]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''stopped'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Marks a note to be held or sustained |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Presto (music)|Presto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''ready'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Very fast |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Prestissimo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''very ready'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Very ''very'' fast, as fast as possible |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[tempo|Accelerando]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''accelerating'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Accelerating |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Affrettando]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''becoming hurried'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Accelerating |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Allargando]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''slowing and broadening'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Slowing down and broadening, becoming more stately and majestic, possibly louder |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Ritardando]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''slowing down'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Decelerating |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Rallentando]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''becoming progressively slower'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Decelerating |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Tempo rubato|Rubato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''robbed'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Free flowing and exempt from steady rhythm |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Tenuto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''sustained'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Holding or sustaining a single note |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Accompagnato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''accompanied'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | The accompaniment must follow the singer who can speed up or slow down at will |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[March (music)|Alla marcia]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''as a march'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | In strict tempo at a marching pace (e.g. 120 bpm) |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[A tempo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''to time'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Return to previous tempo |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[L'istesso tempo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''Same speed'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | At the same speed |}
