== Musical expression (general) == {| border="1" rules="rows" align="center" width="98%" | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Molto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''very'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Used with other terms, such as ''molto allegro'' |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Musical terminology|Assai]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''very'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Used with other terms, such as ''allegro assai'' |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Tempo#Terms for change in tempo|Più]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''more'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Used with other terms, such as ''più mosso'' |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Poco]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''little'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | "A little". Used with other terms, such as ''poco diminuendo'' |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[poco a poco]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''little by little'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | "little by little", "slowly but steadily". Used with other terms, such as '' poco a poco crescendo'' |- id="ma non tanto" | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''ma [[non tanto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''but not so much'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Used with other terms, such as ''adagio ma non tanto'' |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[ma non troppo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''but not too much'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Used with other terms, such as ''allegro ma non troppo'' |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Meno]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''less'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Used with other terms, such as ''meno mosso'' |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Subito]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''suddenly, quickly'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Used with other terms, such as ''subito fortissimo'' |- |}
== Patterns within the musical score == {| border="1" rules="rows" align="center" width="98%" | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Lacuna (music)|Lacuna]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''gap'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A silent pause in a piece of music |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Ossia]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''alternatively'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A secondary passage of music which may be played in place of the original |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Ostinato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''stubborn'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A repeated motif or phrase in a piece of music |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Ritornello]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''little return'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A recurring passage in a piece of Baroque music |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Segue]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''it follows'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A smooth movement from one passage to another with no pause |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Stretto]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''tightened'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | In a fugue, the repeating of a motif by a second voice before the first rendition is completed |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Pensato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''thought'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A composed imaginary note |- |}
== Directions == {| border="1" rules="rows" align="center" width="98%" | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Wiktionary:Attacca|Attacca]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''attach'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Proceed to the next section without pause |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Wiktionary:Cambiare|Cambiare]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''change'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Any change, such as to a new instrument |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Wiktionary:Da Capo|Da Capo (al fine)]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''from the beginning (to the end)'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Abbreviated as D.C., informs the performer to go back to the beginning ''(capo)'' (finishing where the part is marked ''fine'') |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Wiktionary:Dal Segno|Dal Segno]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''from the sign'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Abbreviated as D.S., informs the performer to repeat a specific section marked by a sign ''(segno)'' |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Wiktionary:Divisi|Divisi]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''divided'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Instructs one section to divide into two or more separate sections, each playing a separate part. Often these separate parts are written on the same staff. |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Wiktionary:oppure|Oppure]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''otherwise'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Informs the player of alternative ways to play a passage. See [[Ossia]]. |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[solo (music)|solo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''alone'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A piece or performance to be played by a single musician |}
== Techniques == {| border="1" rules="rows" align="center" width="98%" |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Altissimo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''very high'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Very high |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Arpeggio]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''harp-like'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A chord with the notes spread out in time (rather than sounded simultaneously) |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Acciaccatura]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''crushing'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | An extra, very fast grace note |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Appoggiatura]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''leaning'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A type of ornament that creates a "yearning" effect |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Basso continuo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''continuous bass'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Continuous bass accompaniment by chordal instrument(s) and bass instrument(s) (see figured bass.) |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[A bocca chiusa]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''mouth closed'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Wordless humming in a choral piece |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Chiuso]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''closed'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Calls for a horn to be muted by hand |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Coll'arco]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''with the bow'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Cancels ''col legno'' and ''pizzicato'' (in a string passage, arco is usually expected, as it is the "default" approach, and is not written except at the end of col legno or pizzicato passages.) |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''Colla voce''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''with the voice'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A note to accompanists to play with (in time with) the singer's text, especially when slowing for textual effect |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Col legno]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''with the wood'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Calls for a bowed instrument's strings to be struck with the wood of the bow rather having the hair of the bow drawn over the strings |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Coloratura]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''coloration'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Elaborate ornamentation of a vocal line |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Glissando]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''glide'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A sweeping glide from one pitch to another used for dramatic effect |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Legato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''tied together'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A series of notes played with a smooth connection between them |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Martellato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''hammered'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Notes are strongly accented and detached |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Mute (music)|Con sordino]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''with mute'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Calls for mute to be applied, esp. to [[string instrument]]s. |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Mute (music)|Senza sordino]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''without mute'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Calls for mute to be removed, esp. from [[string instrument]]s. |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Pizzicato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''plucked'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Calls for a bowed instrument to be plucked with the fingers |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Portamento]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''carrying'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A sliding of pitch between two notes |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Portato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''carried'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A style of playing between staccato and legato |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Sforzando (musical direction)|Sforzando]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''using force'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Played with strong, marked emphasis |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Coperti]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''covered'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Of a drum, muted with a cloth |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Una corda]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''one string'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | With the soft pedal, on a piano |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Due corde]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''two strings'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | With the soft pedal, on a piano. For why both terms exist, see [[piano]]. |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Tre corde]]''' or '''[[tutte le corde]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''Three strings'' or ''all the strings'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Cancels an una corda |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Spiccato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''separated'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Playing a stringed instrument by bouncing the bow lightly on the strings |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Tutti]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''all'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A direction for the entire ensemble to play or sing, rather than just a soloist or principal player |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[staccatissimo]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''very detached'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Forcefully exaggerated staccato |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Staccato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''detached'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A form of musical articulation in which notes are distinct and separated from each other by short gaps |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[Scordatura]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''mistuning'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | Alternate tuning (of strings) |- | bgcolor="#ddffdd" | '''[[vibrato]]''' | bgcolor="#f8f8f8" | ''vibrating'' | bgcolor="#ffdddd" | A rapid repetitive variation or undulation in the pitch of a tone |}
