{{short description|Arabic poetic form}} {{one source|date=November 2018}}
[[File:Busti_manuscript.JPG|thumb|A manuscript of [[Abu Al-Fath Al-Busti|Al-Busti]]'s nuniyya, which opens with the line: زيادة المرء في دنياه نقصان (To ascend in one’s world is to decline)]] A '''''nuniyya''''' ([[Arabic]]: نُونِيَّة) is an [[Arabic poetry|Arabic poetic]] [[Poetry#Forms|form]] in which each line ends with an n sound, coming either from the letter ن ([[Nun (letter)|nun]]) or from تنوين (''[[tanwiin]]'' or [[nunation]]). This creates the consonant rhyme scheme of the poem.
Among the most famous ''nuniyyaat'' or nuniyyas are the "Nuniyya of [[Ibn Zaydún]]"<ref>Raymond K. Farrin. “The ‘Nūniyya’ of Ibn Zaydūn: A Structural and Thematic Analysis.” ''Journal of Arabic Literature'', vol. 34, no. 1/2, 2003, pp. 82–106. ''JSTOR'', JSTOR, www.jstor.org/stable/4183477.</ref>, the "Nuniyya of [[Ibn Qayyim]]", the "Nuniyya of [[Imam al-Qahtani al-Andalusi]]", the "Nuniyya of [[Abu Al-Fath Al-Busti]]", and "Elegy for Andalus" by [[Salih ben Sharif al-Rundi|Abu al-Baqaa Ar-Rundi]].
== References == <references />
