{{About||the comic strip titled ''The Captain and the Kids''|The Katzenjammer Kids|the [[Jimmy Buffett]] song ''The Captain and the Kid''|Down to Earth (Jimmy Buffett album)|and|Havaña Daydreamin'}} {{Use British English|date=September 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}} {{Infobox album | name = The Captain & the Kid | type = studio | artist = [[Elton John]] | cover = Captainkid.jpg | alt = | released = 18 September 2006 | recorded = Spring 2006 Center Staging Atlanta | venue = | studio = | genre = [[Rock music|Rock]] | length = 46:02 | label = [[Interscope Records|Interscope]], [[Mercury Records|Mercury]] | producer = Elton John, Matt Still | prev_title = [[Peachtree Road (album)|Peachtree Road]] | prev_year = 2004 | next_title = [[Rocket Man: The Definitive Hits]] | next_year = 2007 }}
'''''The Captain & the Kid''''' is the twenty-eighth [[studio album]] by British singer-songwriter [[Elton John]], released in 2006. It is his second autobiographical album with lyricist [[Bernie Taupin]], picking up where 1975's ''[[Captain Fantastic and the Brown Dirt Cowboy]]'' left off. ''The Captain & the Kid'' chronicles the events in their lives over those subsequent 30 years.
''The Captain & the Kid'' reached No. 6 in the UK, a considerable improvement over the performance of John's preceding ''[[Peachtree Road (album)|Peachtree Road]]'' in 2004, which peaked at No. 21. It reached No. 18 in the US, before quickly falling off the charts. At concerts in early 2007, John made clear his dissatisfaction with Interscope's promotion for the album, having threatened to terminate his contract with the label.
{{Album ratings | MC = 69/100<ref>{{cite web|title=The Captain & The Kid Reviews |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-captain-the-kid/elton-john |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref> |rev1 = [[AllMusic]] |rev1score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Thomas |first=Stephen |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r854153 |pure_url=yes}} |title=The Captain & the Kid – Elton John : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date=12 September 2006 |accessdate=18 June 2012}}</ref> |rev2 = Being There Magazine |rev2score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Miller |first=Adam D. |url=http://beingtheremag.com/reviewalbum.php?id=521&issue=21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927200619/http://beingtheremag.com/reviewalbum.php?id=521&issue=21 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=27 September 2007 |title=Being There |publisher=Beingtheremag.com |date= |accessdate=9 February 2012 }}</ref> |rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' |rev3score = (A-)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/SHOWBIZ/Music/09/19/ew.mus.elton/ |work=CNN |title=CNN.com – EW review: Elton's best album in decades – Sep 19, 2006}}</ref> |rev4 = ''[[The Independent]]'' |rev4score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=Going out? |url=http://enjoyment.independent.co.uk/music/reviews/article1587824.ece |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080808141004/http://enjoyment.independent.co.uk/music/reviews/article1587824.ece |archivedate=8 August 2008 |title=Album: Elton John – Reviews, Music – The Independent |publisher=Enjoyment.Independent.co.uk |date= |accessdate=18 June 2012}}</ref> |rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' |rev5score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/sep/18/entertainment/et-albums18 |author=Nichols, Natalie |work=articles.latimes.com |publisher=''The Los Angeles Times'' |title=Elton John pauses for a glance back |date=18 September 2006 |accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref> |rev6 = Music Box |rev6score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |author=John Metzger |url=http://www.musicbox-online.com/reviews-2006/elton-john-captain-kid.html |title=Elton John – The Captain & the Kid (Album Review) |publisher=Musicbox-online.com |date= |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> |rev7 = [[PopMatters]] |rev7score = (4/10)<ref>{{cite web |last=O'Neil |first=Tim |url=https://www.popmatters.com/elton-john-the-captain-the-kid-2495716894.html |title=Elton John: The Captain & the Kid < PopMatters |publisher=Popmatters.com |date= |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> |rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' |rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/11520022/review/11715868/the_captain_and_the_kid |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220204801/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/11520022/review/11715868/the_captain_and_the_kid |archivedate=20 February 2009 |title=Rolling Stone Music &#124; Album Reviews |publisher=Rollingstone.com |date= |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> |rev9 = This Is London |rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/music/review-23366153-details/CDs+of+the+week/review.do?reviewId=23366153 |title=CDs of the week &#124; Music |publisher=Thisislondon.co.uk |date= |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> |rev10 = Twisted Ear |rev10score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930185125/http://www.twistedear.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=370&Itemid=31]</ref> }}
==Background== [[Interscope Records]] announced that there would be no physical single released from this album as the emphasis is on presenting the album as a [[concept album|body of work]]. However, a [[promotional recording|radio single]] would be released in "[[The Bridge (Elton John song)|The Bridge]]". The album's booklet has photos of John and Taupin all throughout their career, and in the lyrics section, two songs are included, "Across the River Thames" and "12", which do not appear on the music album. "Across the River Thames" was available as a free download to anyone inserting the CD into their computer. This is the first album created by John and Taupin to have them both together on the cover. This was the last studio album to feature [[Guy Babylon]] on keyboards; he died in 2009 and was replaced by Kim Bullard. This was also [[Bob Birch]]'s last appearance on any of John's solo studio albums before his own death in August 2012 (Birch last appeared on the [[Gnomeo & Juliet (soundtrack)|''Gnomeo and Juliet'' soundtrack]]).
==Track listing== All songs written by [[Elton John]] and [[Bernie Taupin]].
